&#xa0;
[normal]The Parliamentary Advisory Council for Transport Safety 
[normal](
[normal]PACTS
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal]is a registered charity and an Associate Parliamentary Group. Its charitable objective is “To protect human life through the promotion of transport safety for the public benefit”. Its aim is to advise and inform members of the House of Commons and of the H
[normal]ouse of Lords on air, rail and road safety issues. It brings together safety professionals and legislators to identify research-based solutions to transport safety problems having regard to cost, effectiveness, achievability and acceptability. 
[normal]PACTS belie
[normal]ves the issue of safety at level crossings to be important and 
[normal]topical and 
[normal]welcomes th
[normal]e Committee’s 
[normal]inquiry
[normal]. 
[normal]With some 
[normal]7,500 to 8,000 
[normal]level crossings
[normal] in Great Britain, 
[normal]level crossings
[normal] represent the largest single risk of catastrophic train 
[normal]accident
[normal] on Brit
[normal]ain's rail network. In addition, 
[normal]despite a generally good rail safety record, 
[normal]there are around 
[normal]nine
[normal] 
[normal]people
[normal] killed in
[normal] level crossing accidents each year
[normal],
[normal] mainly
[normal] pedestrians and vehicle users
[normal]. 
[normal]The inquiry is also is important because s
[normal]afety at level crossin
[normal]gs is a complex matter and requires coordinated action from Network Rail, 
[normal]RSSB, 
[normal]ORR, TOCs, the highway authorities, the local police, British Transport Police and other agencies. The law governing level crossings is 
[normal]seen as 
[normal]outdated and the Law Commission 
[normal]is considering reform.
[normal] Scrutiny by the Committee may help to ensure that al
[normal]l
[normal] parties contribute and in a timely fashion. 
[normal]This submission follows the questions listed in the Committee’s inquiry terms of reference
[normal] 
[normal]Accident data suggest that
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]by international standards 
[normal]safety
[normal],
[normal] risk at level crossings is 
[normal]relatively 
[normal]well controlled in the UK. The R
[normal]ail 
[normal]S
[normal]afety and 
[normal]S
[normal]tandards 
[normal]B
[normal]oard (RSSB)
[normal] reports
[normal] that there were four pedest
[normal]rian fatalities and five road vehicle occupant fatalities on 
[normal]Great 
[normal]Britain’s mainline railway in 2012/13. There were ten collisions between trains and road vehicles, rather fewer than the 10-year average of 13.
[normal] The European Railway Agency reports
[normal]5
[normal] that the
[normal] UK has the 
[normal]lowest
[normal] fatality risk at level crossings in the EU (19 deaths per billion train kilometres). The worst performing country in the EU had a fatality risk more than 28 times higher.
[normal] The UK has a slightly lower density of level crossings than the EU
[normal] average (41 crossing per 100 kilometres
[normal] of track, compared to the EU average of 50)
[normal] 
[normal]Table 1 presents aggregated data on level crossing fatalities and all road fatalities in the European Union.
[normal] Level crossing fatalities account for 
[normal]just over
[normal] 1% of all r
[normal]oad user fatalities in the EU. 
